1. ANALYZE the log and identify the root cause.
2. PLAN your fix.
3. When touching structured data or external tool output, use safe parsers/serializers (avoid string interpolation), validate required fields/schema before use, and use atomic/locked writes when appending to shared artifacts.
4. When handling user inputs (CLI args, config values, env vars), apply normalization (case-insensitive, trimmed whitespace) and use strict validation that rejects malformed inputs; ensure validation logic runs consistently across all code paths and is not skipped by early returns. Treat empty or whitespace-only environment variable values as "not set" rather than letting them override valid configuration.
5. When returning early or handling edge cases, ensure appropriate user-facing notifications (log/debug/warn) are provided—avoid silent failures without explanation.
6. When fixing tests, ensure proper isolation: async tests must await all background operations; mock/timer/global setup must have symmetric teardown in teardown hooks or `finally` blocks (not just at test end); shared module-level state must be reset in setup hooks; allocated filesystem resources (temp dirs) cleaned up in teardown hooks; all declared config options should be referenced in code. Ensure mock return values match actual values produced by the code under test (not stale or placeholder strings).
7. When ordering operations, ensure failures happen before user-visible side effects (validate inputs, check subscriptions/permissions before creating persistent resources). Verify that wrapper/utility methods don't perform unintended side effects beyond their stated purpose (e.g., a "check" method should not create resources). Store HTTP/stream response bodies in a variable before branching—they can only be consumed once. Increment retry/attempt counters before the operation, not after success.
8. APPLY the fix using 'edit'.
9. VERIFY with a quick targeted check (e.g., compile the affected file, run the specific failing test). You MAY run the checks script (e.g., ./checks.sh or the command in `{{ check_cmd }}`) using the 'bash' tool to verify your fix. Prefer targeted invocations over running the full CI pipeline.
